<dl id="n08067g"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n08" href="#n08067g">N08 (VI.B.6)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n08all.htm#n08067g"> 67(g)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> dream (OE = joy) / bread (OE = bit)</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">In some words the old native form has survived, but has adopted the signification attached in Scandinavian to the corresponding word; thus <i>dream</i> in OE. meant &lsquo;joy&rsquo; &hellip; <i>bread</i> (OE. <i>bread</i> &lsquo;fragment&rsquo;) <small> Otto Jespersen, <a name="OJGS" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#OJGS"><cite title="source">The Growth and Structure of the English Language</cite></a>, 4th ed. (Jul 1923) 68</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
